  "prompt": "What is the time complexity for reversing a string through recursion?",
  "response": "Reversing a string through recursion involves breaking down the string into smaller substrings until you reach the base case (typically an empty string or a single character), and then building the reversed string by appending characters in reverse order.\n\nHere's a high-level breakdown of the process:\n\n1. **Base Case**: If the string is empty or has a single character, return the string.\n2. **Recursive Case**: Remove the first character, reverse the remaining substring, and append the first character to the end of the reversed substring.\n\n### Example in Python:\n```python\ndef reverse_string(s):\n    if len(s) <= 1:\n        return s\n    else:\n        return reverse_string(s[1:]) + s[0]\n```\n\n### Time Complexity Analysis\n\n1. **Number of Recursive Calls**: \n   - Each recursive call reduces the string length by 1.\n   - For a string of length `n`, there will be `n` recursive calls.\n\n2. **Work Done in Each Call**:\n   - Slicing the string `s[1:]` takes `O(n)` time in the worst case because it creates a new string by copying the remaining characters.\n   - Appending the character `s[0]` takes `O(1)` time.\n\n3. **Total Time Complexity**:\n   - Since slicing takes `O(n)` time and there are `n` recursive calls, the total time complexity is:\n     \\[\n     O(n) \\times n = O(n^2)\n     \\]\n\n### Space Complexity\n\nThe space complexity is also `O(n^2)` due to the stack space used by recursion (which is `O(n)`) and the additional space used by string slicing in each recursive call (which is `O(n)` per call).\n\n### Summary\n\n- **Time Complexity**: \\( O(n^2) \\)\n- **Space Complexity**: \\( O(n^2) \\)\n\nThis is notably inefficient compared to an iterative approach, which can reverse a string in \\( O(n) \\) time and \\( O(1) \\) additional space.",
